    "discriminators": [
     "The DRY member of the GORE family, and that is the whole discriminator. A snap or crunch is sharp, brittle and bright: high crest_factor, near-zero attack, a fast dry decay and real high-band energy. Everything else in GORE is WET and damped.",
     "Against GORE-SQUISH and GORE-SPLAT: those are LF, low-centroid, heavily damped, low-crest wet events. BONE is the opposite on every one of those axes. This is the most reliable split inside GORE.",
     "Against GORE-STAB, which UCS defines as 'more crunchy than a SQUISH': a STAB is a wet/dry HYBRID — a crunch embedded in a squish — so it sits numerically between BONE and SQUISH and files will straddle the two. That is what keeps this narrowable rather than separable.",
     "A crunch (as opposed to a clean snap) is a burst of many micro-fractures, so transient_count well above 1 is normal here."
    ],
